{
  "The chi-square statistic formula is:": "",
  "Summation of (O + E)": "",
  "Summation of (O - E)^2 / E": "",
  "Summation of (O - E)": "",
  "(O - E) / E": "",
  "The chi-square statistic sums the squared differences between observed (O) and expected (E) counts, each divided by the expected count.": "",
  "Degrees of freedom for a goodness-of-fit test with 5 categories equals:": "",
  "3": "",
  "4": "",
  "5": "",
  "6": "",
  "For a goodness-of-fit test, df = k - 1 = 5 - 1 = 4, where k is the number of categories.": "",
  "Degrees of freedom for a 3 x 4 contingency table equals:": "",
  "12": "",
  "11": "",
  "7": "",
  "For a contingency table, df = (rows - 1)(columns - 1) = (3 - 1)(4 - 1) = 2 x 3 = 6.": "",
  "A large chi-square value suggests:": "",
  "Small sample size": "",
  "The observed data differ significantly from expected": "",
  "Good fit between observed and expected": "",
  "No association between variables": "",
  "A large chi-square value indicates large discrepancies between observed and expected frequencies, providing evidence against the null hypothesis.": "",
  "Expected counts in a chi-square test should all be at least:": "",
  "1": "",
  "10": "",
  "The chi-square approximation is valid when all expected cell counts are at least 5. Below this threshold, the approximation becomes unreliable.": "",
  "If chi-square = 0, this means:": "",
  "The test is invalid": "",
  "Observed counts match expected counts exactly": "",
  "Maximum discrepancy between observed and expected": "",
  "The p-value is 0": "",
  "When chi-square = 0, every observed count equals its expected count perfectly — there is zero discrepancy.": "",
  "The chi-square distribution is always:": "",
  "Negative, taking values below zero for large samples": "",
  "Normal, following a symmetric bell-shaped distribution": "",
  "Symmetric, centered around its mean with equal tails": "",
  "Non-negative (greater than or equal to 0)": "",
  "Chi-square values are sums of squared terms and therefore can never be negative.": "",
  "The expected frequency for a cell in an independence test equals:": "",
  "(Row total times column total) divided by grand total": "",
  "Grand total divided by number of cells": "",
  "Observed count": "",
  "Row total times column total": "",
  "Expected count = (row total x column total) / grand total. This formula gives the count you would expect if the row and column variables were independent.": "",
  "A p-value of 0.02 from a chi-square test at alpha = 0.05 means:": "",
  "Accept the null hypothesis": "",
  "Reject the null hypothesis (evidence against H-null)": "",
  "The data are normally distributed": "",
  "Fail to reject the null hypothesis": "",
  "Since p = 0.02 < alpha = 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. There is statistically significant evidence against H-null.": "",
  "The chi-square distribution shape is:": "",
  "Always flat and uniform across its entire range of possible values": "",
  "Always symmetric and centered around the mean regardless of the degrees of freedom": "",
  "Always bell-shaped and identical to the standard normal distribution at every df value": "",
  "Right-skewed for small df, approaching symmetric for large df": "",
  "The chi-square distribution is right-skewed, especially with few degrees of freedom. As df increases, it becomes more symmetric and approaches a normal shape.": "",
  "What is a goodness-of-fit test?": "",
  "A chi-square test that checks if observed frequencies match a hypothesized distribution": "",
  "A test that measures correlation": "",
  "A test that checks if data are normally distributed": "",
  "A test that compares two means": "",
  "A goodness-of-fit test compares observed category counts to the counts expected under a hypothesized distribution to see if the data 'fit' the model.": "",
  "What is a test of independence?": "",
  "A test for equal variances": "",
  "A test that uses one continuous variable": "",
  "A chi-square test using a two-way contingency table to determine if two categorical variables are associated": "",
  "A test that compares a single sample mean to a known value": "",
  "A test of independence uses a contingency table to examine whether there is an association between two categorical variables from a single sample.": "",
  "What is a test of homogeneity?": "",
  "A chi-square test that checks if the distribution of a categorical variable is the same across different populations": "",
  "A test for equal variances across multiple groups to verify the assumption of homoscedasticity": "",
  "A test for normality used to verify that the data follows a Gaussian distribution in each sample": "",
  "A test that checks if the mean is the same across groups using analysis of variance methodology": "",
  "A homogeneity test compares the distribution of a categorical variable across two or more populations to see if they share the same proportions.": "",
  "What does the null hypothesis state in a test of independence?": "",
  "The two variables are dependent": "",
  "The proportions differ across groups": "",
  "The two categorical variables are independent (no association)": "",
  "The means of the groups are equal": "",
  "H-null in a test of independence states that the two categorical variables have no association — knowing one tells you nothing about the other.": "",
  "What does 'Fisher's exact test' refer to?": "",
  "An exact test for association in a contingency table, used when expected counts are too small for chi-square": "",
  "A large-sample chi-square test": "",
  "A test developed by Fisher for comparing means": "",
  "A test for normality of residuals": "",
  "Fisher's exact test computes exact p-values for 2x2 (or small) contingency tables and is preferred when expected cell counts are below 5, making the chi-square approximation unreliable.": "",
  "What does 'observed count' (O) mean in a chi-square test?": "",
  "The actual count recorded in the data for each category or cell": "",
  "The count predicted by the null hypothesis": "",
  "The count after removing outliers": "",
  "The average of all cell counts": "",
  "Observed counts are the raw frequencies actually collected from the data in each category or cell of a contingency table.": "",
  "What does 'expected count' (E) mean in a chi-square test?": "",
  "The count the researcher hopes to observe": "",
  "The maximum possible count in any cell": "",
  "The observed count divided by 2": "",
  "The count that would be expected if the null hypothesis were true": "",
  "Expected counts are the theoretical counts you would expect to see if H-null were true. They serve as the baseline for measuring how far the observed data deviate.": "",
  "What does 'contingency table' mean?": "",
  "A two-way table displaying the frequency counts for combinations of two categorical variables": "",
  "A backup plan for statistical analysis": "",
  "A table that lists continuous data points in order": "",
  "A table that displays means and standard deviations": "",
  "A contingency table (also called a cross-tabulation) organizes data into rows and columns representing categories of two variables, with cell entries showing the count in each combination.": "",
  "What is the difference between independence and homogeneity tests?": "",
  "They use the same chi-square calculation but differ in study design: independence uses one sample, homogeneity uses multiple populations": "",
  "Independence tests are for continuous data and homogeneity tests are for categorical data": "",
  "They use different formulas and different degrees of freedom": "",
  "There is no difference at all": "",
  "Both use the same chi-square formula and same df calculation. The difference is conceptual: independence examines two variables from one sample; homogeneity compares one variable's distribution across separate populations.": "",
  "What does rejecting H-null in a chi-square test tell you?": "",
  "One variable causes the other, establishing a direct causal relationship between the two factors": "",
  "There is sufficient evidence of association, but chi-square does not tell you the direction or strength": "",
  "The test must be repeated with a larger sample size before any valid conclusions can be drawn": "",
  "The variables are certainly dependent and the association will hold in all future samples as well": "",
  "Chi-square tests detect whether an association exists but do not measure its direction, strength, or causal nature. Additional analysis (like Cramer's V) is needed to quantify the effect.": "",
  "A candy company claims their bags contain 20% red, 30% blue, 25% green, 15% yellow, and 10% orange candies. A student counts 300 candies and finds: 48 red, 102 blue, 72 green, 42 yellow, and 36 orange. What are the expected counts for red and blue?": "",
  "Red: 48, Blue: 102": "",
  "Red: 50, Blue: 100": "",
  "Red: 75, Blue: 75": "",
  "Red: 60, Blue: 90": "",
  "Expected counts: Red = 300 x 0.20 = 60, Blue = 300 x 0.30 = 90. These are the counts expected if the company's claimed proportions are correct.": "",
  "A university surveys 500 students about their preferred study method (library, dorm, cafe) and academic year (freshman, sophomore, junior, senior). This creates a 3 x 4 contingency table. How many degrees of freedom does the chi-square test of independence have?": "",
  "df = (3 - 1)(4 - 1) = 2 x 3 = 6. The table has 3 rows (study method) and 4 columns (academic year).": "",
  "A geneticist crosses two heterozygous pea plants and observes 315 round-yellow, 108 round-green, 101 wrinkled-yellow, and 32 wrinkled-green offspring. The expected Mendelian ratio is 9:3:3:1. With 556 total offspring, what is the expected count for round-yellow?": "",
  "139": "",
  "315": "",
  "278": "",
  "312.75": "",
  "The 9:3:3:1 ratio means 9/16 should be round-yellow. Expected count = 556 x (9/16) = 556 x 0.5625 = 312.75.": "",
  "A hospital compares patient satisfaction (satisfied, neutral, dissatisfied) across three departments (surgery, ER, pediatrics). The row totals are Surgery: 200, ER: 150, Pediatrics: 100. The column totals are Satisfied: 250, Neutral: 120, Dissatisfied: 80. What is the expected count for the Surgery-Satisfied cell?": "",
  "111.1": "",
  "125.0": "",
  "250.0": "",
  "100.0": "",
  "Grand total = 200 + 150 + 100 = 450. Expected = (Row total x Column total) / Grand total = (200 x 250) / 450 = 50,000 / 450 = 111.1.": "",
  "A market researcher surveys 400 consumers about brand preference (A, B, C, D). She expects equal preference across all four brands. She observes: A = 120, B = 95, C = 90, D = 95. The chi-square value is 4.75. With df = 3 and a critical value of 7.815 at alpha = 0.05, what is the conclusion?": "",
  "The test is invalid because expected counts are too small": "",
  "Reject H-null; preferences are significantly different": "",
  "Brand A is definitively preferred": "",
  "Fail to reject H-null; there is not enough evidence that preferences differ from equal": "",
  "Chi-square = 4.75 < critical value 7.815, so we fail to reject H-null. Expected count for each brand = 400/4 = 100 (all >= 5). The observed differences are not statistically significant.": "",
  "A school district examines whether school lunch choice (hot meal, sandwich, salad) is independent of grade level (elementary, middle, high). The chi-square test yields chi-square = 15.8 with df = 4. The critical value at alpha = 0.01 is 13.28. What is the conclusion?": "",
  "The test cannot be performed with these degrees of freedom": "",
  "Fail to reject H-null; lunch choice and grade level are independent": "",
  "Reject H-null; there is significant evidence that lunch choice and grade level are associated": "",
  "The p-value is greater than 0.05": "",
  "Chi-square = 15.8 > critical value 13.28 at alpha = 0.01, so we reject H-null. Lunch choice and grade level are significantly associated even at the 1% significance level.": "",
  "A die is rolled 120 times with results: 1 (25 times), 2 (17 times), 3 (19 times), 4 (22 times), 5 (18 times), 6 (19 times). If the die is fair, each expected count is 20. What is the chi-square contribution from face 1?": "",
  "0.25": "",
  "5.00": "",
  "25.00": "",
  "1.25": "",
  "Chi-square contribution from face 1 = (O - E)^2 / E = (25 - 20)^2 / 20 = 25/20 = 1.25.": "",
